args: Three years before the current day,\nin a hall for interviewing potential recruits...
Thank you for having me here today.
The name's Victor. Tell me why you\napplied to become a messenger.
Um, because...because I want to\ntell people things.
Well, I read in a book that you can...\nEr, I mean, that one can...
I'm sorry. I'm not very good at talking.
Yet that didn't deter you from applying\nfor this position...
Well, when I was a child, I read about how\nit's important to tell others how you feel.
And if you can't speak your feelings aloud,\nyou can do it with letters or other ways.
I took that to heart, and ever since have...
Well, I thought there must be some way\nfor ME to tell people things.
I see. And yet, this is a job that requires\nstamina and speed in addition to speaking.\nAre you an active person?
But even if I'm kind of slow, I'll run as fast\nas I possibly can to deliver my message!
Hmm, I see. Well, I have a few more\nquestions for you. Please reply with\na simple ＂yes＂ or ＂no＂ answer to each.
Are you aware that being a messenger\nrequires you to work in foreign countries,\nincluding some that may be hostile?

Are you aware you will sometimes be
tasked with delivering orders to dangerous
places? And that as such, this is not
a job for the faint of heart?
Such danger, yet you applied regardless.\nDoes the act of telling things to others\nreally mean so much to you?
Thank you, Noelle. That is all.\nYou will have your answer soon.

Every applicant thus far has boasted of
their agility or stamina. Whereas Noelle...
Well, let us just say I've never had an
interview quite like that before.
She lacks speed, she lacks stamina,\nand she can barely hold a conversation.
I wouldn't entrust her with the task of\ndelivering an advertising flier, much less\nany kind of important directive.
I'm not sure what even possessed\nthe poor child to apply.
If the ability to deliver things was all we\ncared about, we could leave this job\nto any old letter carrier.
What we need is the resolve to deliver\na message in ANY circumstances,\nregardless of the danger involved.
A messenger must understand the import\nof their task and have the drive to\novercome all obstacles in their way.
And you think she has such qualities?

Speed and stamina can be trained,
but a new mindset? Not so much.
I wish to see how she takes to an
aggressive training regimen.
If that is your decision,\nI will abide by it.
I will inform the girl that she has been\nchosen and arrange for her training\nto begin at once.
This one has a bright future ahead of her,\nmy friend. Just you wait.
*sigh* Passing on messages accurately\nis surprisingly difficult.
I ended up having to write all of today's\nmissives down in letters, too.
I'm really not suited to this job, am I?
Failing during training isn't the great\nshame you seem to think it is.
Nor is the spoken word the only way\nto reliably relay information.
If you have time to worry, you have time\nto work on bettering yourself.
I take it you received your appointment.
Good. Your training is over—from this\nday forth, you will serve as a messenger\nunder my command.
After my appointment, I began to serve\nas a messenger for the Commander.
Sometimes I was even ordered to deliver\nmessages to allies in enemy territory.
Time didn't make me better at talking—\nand there were some parts I didn't enjoy—\nbut I still found my new life fulfilling.
But one day, all of that came to an end...
Noelle. I hereby relieve you of\nyour current appointment.
Because your former commander has run\naway, leaving his country and everything\nbehind.
You will be informed of your new task\nshortly—until then, you are to stand by.\nThat is all. Dismissed!
Wait, please! I don't understand!\nWhy would he do something like that?!
Know your place, messenger!\nWe are done here!
I could only assume everyone had been\nordered to keep silent about whatever\nit was the Commander had done.
I learned he had left the country,\nbut I knew there had to be a reason.
And so I set about trying to gather\ninformation as I continued my work.
